The interactions between the CNDs and the target ion allow for sensitive and selective detection. Different binding interactions, such as coordination, electrostatic effects, and oxidation–reduction processes, may be the basis of Fe2+ detection by CNDs [2]. Herein, a PET process is proposed (Fig. 5
                        ) to address the quenching mechanism of the N, B-doped CNDs by Fe2+ ions [12,35]. There is a less stable electron in the Fe2+ structure at the 3d6 electronic configuration, compared to the stable configuration of 3d5. The electrons from Fe2+ ions could transfer to acceptor sites of N, B-doped CNDs, becoming more stable Fe3+ ions and forming quenched complex N, B-doped CNDs-[Fe3+]n 
                        [12].
